    <text>
        <front>
            <div type="summary">
                <p>
                    Letter from Norman Leys to Leonard Woolf requesting clarification on some issues regarding the publishing of a revised and improved version of a pamphlet.
                </p>
            </div>
        </front>
        <body>
            <div type="letter">
                <opener>
                    <add place="above">MS 2750/255/97</add>
                    <dateline>
                        <date when="1926-02-16">
                         16-2-26
                        </date>
                    </dateline>
                    <salute>
                        Dear <persName><surname>Woolf</surname></persName>,</lb>
                    </salute>
                </opener>
                <p>
                    It was very nice of you to </lb>
                    put it as you did. But I don’t really </lb>
                    know if you <emph rend="underlined">want</emph> to publish an </lb>
                    improved version of that pamphlet. </lb>
                    The chief question to be answered is </lb>
                    whether the public could be reached </lb> 
                    better by the <orgName>Hogarth Press</orgName><note><p>A book publishing imprint of Penguin Random House that was founded in 1917 by Virigina and Lenoard Woolf.</p></note> or by the </lb>
                    <orgName><choice><abbr>I.L.P</abbr><expan>Independent Labour Party</expan></choice></orgName><note><p>The Independent Labour Party was a British political party of the established in 1893.</p></note>? I suppose your heart </lb>
                    answers ‘how the hell can I tell’?' </lb>
                    Subsidiary <supplied reason="strikethrough" cert="high"><del>auestions</del></supplied> questions are 1. What </lb>
                    price would you sell at? 2 </pb>
                    2. Who would stand the cost and </lb>
                    profit or loss – me or you? </lb>
                    3. Would copies be sent out for </lb>
                    review? 4. <choice><orig>Right</orig><reg><corr>Might</corr></reg></choice> this pamphlet </lb>
                    interfere with the sale of the cheap </lb>
                    <choice><abbr>ed.</abbr><expan>edition</expan></choice> of <title type="book">Kenya</title><note><p>A book written by Norman Leys, published by the Hogarth Press in in 1924.</p></note>? </lb>
                    Could you answer some of these </lb>
                    questions?  And if <persName>Keynes'</persName> pamphlet </lb>
                    has stopped selling, may I have </lb>
                    a copy?</lb>
                    I am very glad you told me the </lb>
                    pamphlet needs rewriting. For </lb>
                    weeks on end I am incapable of </pb>
                    <add place="above">MS2750/255/97</add> 3 </lb>
                    my best. And my best is good </lb> 
                    enough for publication in so </lb>
                    restricted a field that I shall </lb>
                    have to be very careful not to let </lb>
                    the success of <title type="book">‘Kenya’</title> tempt me </lb>
                    to put out worthless <choice><orig>shitt</orig><reg>shit</reg></choice>. In this </lb>
                    care I shall wait a week or two </lb>
                    and try to improve the pam-</lb>phlet.</lb>
                    I do wish people would realise </lb>
                    that in <supplied reason="ink smudge" cert="high">many</supplied> ways I am rather </lb>
                    stupid. I can arrange, <supplied reason="ink smudge" cert="high">clarify</supplied> </lb>
                    and in interpret data, can analyze </pb>
                    and estimate — even foresee so </lb>
                    far as to plan <add place="above">a</add> <add place="below">&#94;</add> coordinate <unclear reason="bad handwriting" cert="medium">policy</unclear>.</lb>
                    But the facts must be in full </lb>
                    sight. I cannot ‘sense’ things.</lb>
                    So I can contribute nothing original</lb>
                    except what arises from the </lb>
                    data themselves when I set them </lb>
                    in true relation.</lb> 
                    I hope Mrs. <persName><surname>Woolf</surname></persName> is better, </lb>
                    long ago.
                </p>
                <closer>
                    <salute>
                        Yours 
                    </salute>
                    <signed>Norman Leys</lb>
                    <signed/>
                    <seg type="postscript">
                        Please send enclosed to <unclear reason="'ink smudge" cert="high">the</unclear> </lb> 
                        unknown donor of €20
                    </seg>
                </closer>
